g.text: Pile of Eternite: An inconspicuous pile of the roofing material, eternite.
The pile of eternite looks stranger now that Cuno told you about his... pad.
Perception (Sight): It reveals no secrets at this time.
Conceptualization: Rhythmic pattern -- calms your mind. Mammals like this stuff.
Inland Empire: Hard to say, it's gone now. Feelings pass, you see. Especially the small ones.

Encyclopedia: Glad you asked. When junior researcher Õlari Taal invented eternite in the Värtna Polytechnic Institute, some thirty odd years ago, he thought it would last forever -- hence the name eternite. Sadly the only lasting thing turned out to be the material's highly carcinogenic effect.
Perception (Sight): There it is! You see a shabby little door.
You: Why am I looking at this pile of the roofing material?
Jump to: [Pile of Eternite: "An inconspicuous pile of the roofin..."]
Pile of Eternite: It's nothing. Someone just left some roofing material slanted against an old shack.
Inland Empire: No, there's more to this. You get this strange *feeling*.
Perception (Sight): Because there's a secret door hidden behind the panels of eternite. That's why they're *too* orderly.
Because unless Cuno lied, you should just be able to pull the panels aside.
Perception (Sight): Because it's nice and orderly. Well laid pallet. Easy on the eyes.
Kim Kitsuragi: "What is this, then? A tool shed?" He peeks inside. "Let's investigate."
"So this is the shack Cuno mentioned... Let's take a look inside, then."
